<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<Weakness xmlns="http://cwe.mitre.org/cwe-7" ID="196" Name="Unsigned to Signed Conversion Error" Abstraction="Variant" Structure="Simple" Status="Draft">
         <Description>The product uses an unsigned primitive and performs a cast to a signed primitive, which can produce an unexpected value if the value of the unsigned primitive can not be represented using a signed primitive.</Description>
         <Extended_Description>Although less frequent an issue than signed-to-unsigned conversion, unsigned-to-signed conversion can be the perfect precursor to dangerous buffer underwrite conditions that allow attackers to move down the stack where they otherwise might not have access in a normal buffer overflow condition. Buffer underwrites occur frequently when large unsigned values are cast to signed values, and then used as indexes into a buffer or for pointer arithmetic.</Extended_Description>
         <Related_Weaknesses>
            <Related_Weakness Nature="ChildOf" CWE_ID="681" View_ID="1000" Ordinal="Primary" />
             <Related_Weakness Nature="ChildOf" CWE_ID="681" View_ID="1305" Ordinal="Primary" />
			 <Related_Weakness Nature="ChildOf" CWE_ID="681" View_ID="1340" Ordinal="Primary" />
            <Related_Weakness Nature="CanAlsoBe" CWE_ID="124" View_ID="1000" />
            <Related_Weakness Nature="CanAlsoBe" CWE_ID="120" View_ID="1000" />
         </Related_Weaknesses>
